We attended the 2025 Farm Progress show in Decatur, Illinois where discussions focused on Ag Cycle demand trends including ongoing geopolitical challenges, and more importantly innovation across autonomy and the broader Precision Ag envelope.

2025 Farm Progress underscored Ag equipment demand continues to face uncertainty, but bolstered our conviction in Precision Ag proliferation. Demand commentary continues to point to farmers taking a cautious approach to ordering ahead of 2026. OEM preliminary outlooks for 2026, meanwhile, remain far more mixed. DE sounded cautiously optimistic on 2026 but noted it remains too early to tell given macro uncertainty. CNH alluded to an expectation for flattish global industry sales (NA flat to down and Europe/LatAm flat to up). AGCO meanwhile noted it continues to expect 2025 to mark the bottom and for all its four major regions to be up YoY in 2026. All in all, underscoring a lack of consensus and ongoing uncertainty around the demand outlook for 2026. Industry trends aside, product displays continue to highlight a focus on Precision Ag innovation, where the more notable takeaway in our view was a further divergence in the monetization strategies being implemented. DE noted moving its See & Spray product to a pay for what you save methodology while CNH has clearly moved further away from subscription based models in favor of one time capital cost models. Interestingly, both highlight their approaches as potential drivers of improved interest in adoption of new technology and demand for new products. And lastly, on the point of Precision Ag, this was the first year where we saw a material presence from aerial autonomous technology at Farm progress including the likes of Pyka (Pelican 2), Yamaha Fazer, and other drone manufacturers which we believe underscores our view that while we remain early days of adoption of newer autonomous technologies, we are nonetheless at a potentially meaningful inflection point where acceptance and interest in these technologies is becoming more widespread. Something which bodes well for future penetration of higher value Precision Ag technologies See below for detailed key takeaways from meetings with the three major Ag OEMs AGCO, CNH, and Deere.

- Tariff remains an outstanding risk: Management acknowledged that AGCO is responding to tariff impacts by raising prices across its portfolio, including low to mid single digit increases in North America (2-3% globally). These pricing actions are positioned as one lever to help offset cost pressures and preserve margins for the business. However, there was no discussion of incremental impact of Section 232 expansion to 407 HTUS codes, which we think remains a risk for the OEM group as a whole.

- AGCO continues to expect 2025 to be the trough of the Ag cycle, and although it is seeing farmers remaining cautious about their equipment purchases, it nevertheless continues to expect modest industry growth across all four of its key regions in 2026. Regarding its Early Order Program in North America, management noted these only just started a week ago and thus it plans to provide an update with its 3Q25 results.

- PTx Tech Innovation: Launch of FarmENGAGE, a new digital data platform designed as a mixed fleet operations management, was the most notable development highlighted as a central part of PTx. It is now offered in all model year 2026 Fendt and Massey tractors allowing farmers to plan, monitor, and analyze field activity remotely. It will be monetized by a standard three year subscription included on new machines and annual renewals thereafter. This important launch is notable as it gives the company a competitive brand agnostic solution to compete against peers' platforms (i.e. Deere's Operations Center). Also, AGCO is launching satellite Starlink connectivity with the solution set to come to markets through the PTx network later this year.

- PTx Channel Developments: AGCO highlighted that a major ongoing opportunity is to further build out the channel, with a strong push to increase the number of full-line elite dealers. There are now 44 elite dealers globally, with a focus on North America and South America, expected to roughly double by the end of 2025 and continue at a similar pace into 2026. Management emphasized that penetration of dealers is a better measure of success than the number of dealers, highlighting progress in unlocking Massey dealers as PTx dealer having risen to 244 dealers onboarded to PTx this year.

- North America Fendt Competitive Dynamics: Fendt brand appears to garner more interest from larger strategic accounts that previously would not have had the opportunity to trial the brand. Management noted that this increase in demo activity is driven by 1) its dealer expansion efforts, including FarmerCore, 2) brand value, and 3) its competitive technology offering.

- North America Fendt Distribution: AGCO noted Fendt currently has 80% dealer coverage in North America, highlighting the FarmerCore initiative aiming to bring parts and service closer to the farm by utilizing mobile assets and digital channels. With AGCO's goal of 50% or more of service work to be done on farm, FarmerCore is being launched in North and South America, primarily with Fendt and Valtra dealers. Massey dealers are also beginning to adopt the initiative.

CNH highlighted the launch of its Newlolland e- commerce platform which would provide a more seamless purchasing experience for customers. The initial focus is on smaller Newlolland equipment, with plans to eventually roll this out to Case IH.

- Tech integration: CNH targets for nearly all precision capabilities to run on its in house tech stack by model year 2026, powering its digital systems across the portfolio. As of now, few products remain which are being sourced from a third party and need to be integrated in house, indicating continued progress in the company's integration of its Raven acquisition and development of a more vertically integrated offering.

- Regarding demand, CNH emphasized dealers remaining very cautious due to interest rates and geopolitical uncertainty, however, it continues to believe that 2025 is the trough for the Global Ag cycle. While it did not provide specific numbers on its Early Order Programs (EOPs), CNH did note these were coming in as expected. Commenting on the broader industry outlook for 2026, CNH noted that while global ag equipment cycle may be bottoming, it still sees a bit of a mixed picture across regions expecting broader industry sales in North America to be flat to down, offset by Europe/ LatAm which it expects to be flat to up.

- Section 232 code expansion an incremental tariff headwind. Management indicated they are still working to quantify the full impact of the expanded Section 232 tariffs to include 407 HTUS codes. While these will no doubt be an incremental headwind to the business, levers such as surcharges and ongoing self-help can be used to mitigate.

- Tech and Innovation: Farmers have given positive feedback on FieldOps, and the launch of the second-generation cotton picker with integrated round baling underscores CNH's continued push to advance technology.

- Brazil: Despite weak ag fundamentals in Brazil, management remains confident that it is adequately reserved for the current situation and for the company's ability to navigate the current market challenges.

- New Holland: The focus for this brand is to meet the company's five pillars. This was underscored by the emphasis on simplification and cost savings for customers through products such as CR11 Twin Rotor Combine now enhanced with IntelliSense automation and FieldOps connectivity. The focus on the quality pillar was routinely noted as a key focus in how they run this business. On the point of dealer integration, the company noted it is seeing good level of interest from their dealers in expanding their offering across CNH brands.

- Case IH: The focus of discussions on Case IH centered on continued innovation and integration with precision ag technology. Product discussions/ displays highlighted FieldOps, Steigert, SenseApply, AI Assist tools, and Harvest Command among others. As mentioned earlier, the company's go to market strategy on precision ag technology appears to have fully shifted to a one time capital cost or purchase model and away from subscription based monetization strategies. Importantly, management indicated that higher

levels of up front cost in this go to market strategy have not been an impediment to equipment demand. On the contrary, it believes it may be an incentive driving demand for machines that offer the latest technology and gives the farmer access to greater savings opportunities â€“ for instance, it's SenseApply technology (available also via retrofit) can generate between 5- 10% savings or as high as 70% savings when including weed spot spray technology

- Ag Cycle: Deere reiterated its earlier comments provided at F3Q earnings. Namely that EOPs for Sprayers are not necessarily a read through for other larger product verticals like Combines where EOPs are still underway or broader tractor demand. That said, the company's tone continued to reflect a more cautiously optimistic view on 2026 while noting that it remains too early to tell, in particular given ongoing macro uncertainty.- Deere shifted to a new "pay for what you save" revenue model for See & Spray, where the Operations Center quantifies farmers' input savings from technologies like See & Spray and ExactShot. Deere then gets paid on a proportion of those savings, further aligning the company to its ability to add value to the farmer's operations and increasing farmer's ROI.- Autonomy: Today the company's efforts are focused on Tillage, but DE highlighted that learnings from tillage can accelerate rollout to other products over time, with adoption supported by flexible pay models such as usage-based or subscriptions.- Planters: Deere showcased its planter products, with a particular focus on its FurrowVision and ExactEmerge technologies. While its FurrowVision system was launched a couple of years ago, model year 2026 will be the first time the technology is available as a factory-installed option and not just as a retrofit. Regarding its ExactEmerge planter, which has ExactShot technology, the company noted it is its most popular planter.- Combine Enhancements: Deere highlighted how its products continue to be enhanced to add greater value to the farmer, with predictive ground speed automation for example driving 20% efficiency gains. Importantly, DE outlined several automation and efficiency enhancements to its 2026 combines including enhanced predictive ground speed automation that offer compatibility to additional crops, auto track turn automation, etc.- Self Propelled Forage harvesters: Deere introduced several new models between its F8 and F9 series, with pro touch harvest and ground-speed automation, enabling inexperienced operators to produce on par with experienced operators.

- Construction & Forestry segment comments: Deere noted that incremental discounting appears to be successfully stimulated demand, with orders showing a positive response. Notably, DE indicated that order momentum remained positive through July and August. keeping it cautiously optimistic about the backdrop for this business.

We apply a \(\sim 20x\) multiple to AGCO's 2025e earnings, or the high end of AGCO's historical trading range of \(10.6x - 20.4x\) on trough earnings.
More robust growth in commodity prices Margins expand faster than expected driven by healthy Fendt adoption in the Americas Trimble integration and synergies better than expected Faster debt paydown
Farmer sentiment & commodity prices fail to improve Fendt expansion in North and South America is worse than expected Precision ag introductions fail to gain traction Price/cost weighs on margins

In our base case, Ag Equipment sales decline in 2025 driven by lower commodity crop prices. Construction volumes decline MSD% on the back of a peaking US non- resi market. Margins contract due to lower volumes, offset by the company's cost savings initiatives. As such, we assume that the stock trades on \(\sim 15x\) P/E (NTM) on normalized EPS of \(\) 1\(, roughly in line with shares' historical average.
Stronger crop prices result in stronger Farmer profits and higher equipment demand Stronger than expected US construction spending Precision planting penetration exceeds expectations

Weaker crop prices pressure farmer cash returns Construction demand disappoints and pressures margins Competitive behavior deteriorates pushing prices lower and resulting in share loss and higher margin decrements
